{"id":"2209.04302","submitter":"Belinda Wickes","authors":"Belinda Wickes","title":"Separating Path Systems for the Complete Graph","comments":"27 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  For any graph $G$, a separating path system of $G$ is a family of paths in\n$G$ with the property that for any edges $e,e' \\in E(G)$ there is at least one\npath in the family that contains one of $e$ and $e'$ but not the other. We\ninvestigate the size of the smallest separating path system for $K_n$, denoted\n$f(K_n)$.\n  It is known that $n-1 \\leq f(K_n)\\leq 2n+4$, our main result is a\nconstruction that reduces the upper bound to $f(K_n) \\leq\n\\left(\\frac{21}{16}+o(1)\\right)n$ for sufficiently large $n$, and to $f(K_n)\n\\leq n$ whenever $n=p,p+1$ for prime $p$.\n  A key idea in our construction is to reduce the problem to finding a single\npath with some particular properties we call a Generator Path. These are\ndefined in such a way that the $n$ cyclic rotations of a generator path provide\na separating path system for $K_n$. Hence existence of a generator path for\nsome $K_n$ gives $f(K_n) \\leq n$. We construct such paths for all $K_n$ with $n\n\\leq 20$, and show that generator paths exist whenever $n$ is prime.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 9 Sep 2022 13:51:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-12"}
